footnotes.text: Patients who continue on treatment will be assessed in the same manner
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Provides instruction on how to assess continuing patients, purely operational guidance.

footnotes.text: Every effort should be made to minimize the time between randomization and starting treatment. (i.e. on the same day after randomization)
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Specifies timing constraint for starting treatment relative to randomization, affecting scheduling.

footnotes.text: Informed consent of study procedures and tumor biopsy sample may be obtained prior to the 28-day screening window, if necessary, in order to permit tumor biopsy sample acquisition and analysis (PD-L1 status and, if unknown, EGFR and ALK status) prior to randomization.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Creates conditional logic for when informed consent may be obtained earlier than typical screening window.

footnotes.text: Body weight is recorded along with vital signs.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Provides documentation instruction for vital signs procedure, purely operational.

footnotes.text: Any clinically significant abnormalities detected require a confirmatory ECG.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Creates conditional requirement for additional ECG based on clinical findings.

footnotes.text: If screening laboratory assessments are performed within 3 days prior to Day 1 (first infusion day), they do not need to be repeated at Day 1.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Creates conditional logic based on timing (within 3 days) that affects whether assessments are repeated, impacting both branching and scheduling.

footnotes.text: Free T3 and free T4 will only be measured if TSH is abnormal or if there is clinical suspicion of an AE related to the endocrine system.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Creates conditional requirement for additional lab tests based on TSH results or clinical suspicion.

footnotes.text: For women of childbearing potential only. A urine or serum pregnancy test is acceptable.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Creates conditional requirement for specific population (women of childbearing potential).

footnotes.text: To be administered in line with local practice for patients with non-squamous tumors who will receive pemetrexed if randomized to SoC group.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Creates conditional requirement for specific tumor type and treatment group.

footnotes.text: Results for urea and electrolytes, full blood count, and liver function tests must be available before commencing an infusion (within 3 days).
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Specifies timing requirement for lab results availability before infusion, affecting scheduling.

footnotes.text: In instances where the PRO assessments coincide with a clinic visit, the research nurse or study coordinator should verify that the questionnaire was completed before the visit. If not, the patient should complete the questionnaire prior to any other study procedures and before discussion of disease progression to avoid biasing the patient's responses to the questions.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Provides detailed procedural instructions for PRO assessment timing to avoid bias, operational guidance.

footnotes.text: Informed consent of study procedures and tumor biopsy sample may be obtained prior to the 28-day screening window, if necessary, in order to permit tumor biopsy sample acquisition and analysis prior to randomization.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Creates conditional logic for when biopsy consent may be obtained earlier than typical screening window.

footnotes.text: For patients with unknown status of ALK and/or EGFR NSCLC.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Creates conditional requirement for specific patient population with unknown biomarker status.

footnotes.text: RECIST 1.1 assessments will be performed on CT/MRI images of the chest and abdomen (including liver and adrenal glands). Additional anatomy should be imaged based on signs and symptoms of individual patients at baseline and follow-up. Baseline assessments should be performed no more than 28 days before the date of randomization and, ideally, should be performed as close as possible to and prior to the start of study treatment. The radiological progression confirmatory scans should be performed no less than 4 weeks after the prior assessment of PD and preferably at the next scheduled visit (in the absence of clinically significant deterioration). If an unscheduled assessment was performed and the patient has not progressed, every attempt should be made to perform the subsequent assessments at their next scheduled visit. Treatment through confirmed radiologic PD for patients who may continue to benefit from the durvalumab at the discretion of investigator must be discussed on a case by case basis after consultation with the Sponsor
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Multi-label: Contains both timing constraints (28 days, 4 weeks) affecting scheduling AND conditional logic for progression assessments affecting branching.

footnotes.text: Every effort should be made to minimize the time between randomization and starting treatment. (i.e., on the same day after randomization)
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Specifies timing constraint to minimize time between randomization and treatment start, affecting scheduling.

footnotes.text: Informed consent of study procedures and tumor biopsy sample may be obtained prior to the 28-day screening window, if necessary, in order to permit tumor biopsy sample acquisition and analysis prior to randomization
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Multi-label: Creates conditional logic (if necessary for biopsy) AND affects scheduling (prior to 28-day window). Both EDC branching and scheduling are affected.

footnotes.text: Before every infusion or administration and as clinically indicated.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Multi-label: Specifies timing (before infusion) AND conditional requirement (as clinically indicated). Both scheduling and branching logic are affected.

footnotes.text: To be collected every 3 weeks prior to the start of infusion and as clinically indicated. If screening laboratory assessments are performed within 3 days prior to Day 1 (first infusion day), they do not need to be repeated at Day 1.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Multi-label: Specifies frequency (every 3 weeks) AND conditional logic (if within 3 days, don't repeat). Both scheduling and branching are affected.

footnotes.text: RECIST 1.1 assessments will be performed on CT/MRI images of the chest and abdomen (including liver and adrenal glands). Additional anatomy should be imaged based on signs and symptoms of individual patients at baseline and follow-up. Baseline assessments should be performed no more than 28 days before the date of randomization and, ideally, should be performed as close as possible to and prior to the start of study treatment. The radiological progression confirmatory scans should be performed no less than 4 weeks after the prior assessment of PD and preferably at the next scheduled visit (in the absence of clinically significant deterioration). If an unscheduled assessment was performed and the patient has not progressed, every attempt should be made to perform the subsequent assessments at their next scheduled visit.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Multi-label: Specifies multiple timing constraints (28 days before randomization, 4 weeks between scans) AND conditional logic (additional anatomy if indicated). Both scheduling and branching are affected.

footnotes.text: Physical exams are described in Section 5.2.2.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: References protocol section for detailed procedures, providing documentation guidance without EDC logic impact.

footnotes.text: The AE/SAE follow-up for SoC is only 30 days
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Specifies different timing constraint for Standard of Care group, affecting scheduling duration.

footnotes.text: WHO/ECOG performance status should also be collected at other site visits that the patient attends, if appropriate site staff are available to collect such information. In addition, WHO performance status should be provided when information on subsequent anticancer therapy is provided, where possible.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Specifies additional collection timepoints and frequency for WHO/ECOG performance status beyond scheduled visits.

footnotes.text: Details of any treatment for NSCLC (including surgery) post the last dose of study treatment must be recorded in the eCRF.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Specifies documentation requirement for post-treatment NSCLC therapy in eCRF without creating conditional logic.

footnotes.text: PFS2 assessment will be performed by the Investigator and defined according to local standard clinical practice and may involve any of the following: objective radiological imaging, symptomatic progression, or death. For patients who discontinue their assigned IP following confirmed progression, available readings of CT/MRI from local practice will be collected from the patients' medical charts while information on subsequent anticancer treatment and/or PFS2 is collected.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Describes PFS2 assessment procedures and data collection methods per local practice without creating EDC logic constraints.

footnotes.text: Patients may be contacted in the week following data cut-offs to confirm survival status. Details of any treatment for NSCLC (including surgery) post the last dose of study treatment must be recorded in the eCRF.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Describes patient contact procedures for survival status confirmation and documentation requirements without EDC logic impact.

footnotes.text: For patients in the durvalumab group only. Immunogenicity samples for durvalumab are collected 90 days (3 months) (+ 7 days) after treatment with the applicable drug ends. In addition a final immunogenicity sample is taken 6 months (+ 7 days) after treatment with the applicable drug ends.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Multi-label: Creates conditional branch for durvalumab patients only AND specifies specific timing windows (90 days, 6 months).

footnotes.text: Patients will complete PROs using handheld devices at home.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Describes PRO completion method and location without creating conditional logic or scheduling constraints.

footnotes.text: Only for patients yet to progress, RECIST 1.1 assessments will be performed on CT/MRI images of the chest and abdomen (including liver and adrenal glands). Additional anatomy should be imaged based on signs and symptoms of individual patients. The radiological progression confirmatory scans should preferably be performed no less than 4 weeks after the prior assessment of PD and preferably at the next scheduled visit (in the absence of clinically significant deterioration). If an unscheduled assessment was performed and the patient has not progressed, every attempt should be made to perform the subsequent assessments at their scheduled visits (relative to the date of randomization). All confirmatory scans should be recorded on the database.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Multi-label: Creates conditional branch for patients yet to progress AND specifies timing constraints (4 weeks minimum, scheduled visits).

footnotes.text: If the patient continues to derive benefit from study treatment, then scans should continue to be collected following the original schedule and analysed by RECIST1.1, even after confirmed radiographic progression.
footnotes.classificationReasoning: Multi-label: Creates conditional branch for patients deriving benefit AND specifies continued scheduling even after progression.
